descript.abstract: The Forest Vegetation Simulator (FVS) is the USDA Forest Service's nationally supported framework for forest growth and yield modeling. A 'variant' is a model calibrated to a specific geographic area. Within each variant, location codes are used to adjust model parameters and determine volume equations. In most variants, location codes are assigned as National Forest codes or National Forest and District codes, but there are a few exceptions. A polygon in this GIS layer represents the location code that could be used as the default based on geographic location alone. There is exactly one location code for every location within the United States. This layer is not intended to identify the only location code, nor even the best for any particular location. Please refer to the FVS documentation (Variant Overviews) for a description of the geographic extent of the data used to develop each location code.
descript.purpose: This GIS layer was designed to provide a unique default FVS location code for any location within the United States based solely on its coordinates. An example of its intended use is the automated assignment of a default location code to a large number of points based on latitude and longitude alone. It is important to understand that the codes in this layer are suggested defaults only, and a user of the FVS model is free to select whatever location code they feel is appropriate for their data.
descript.supplinf: Additional layers of USA States, counties, National Forest System (NFS) boundaries and Robert Bailey's Ecoregion are included. These are the base layers to which the FVS Variant layer was registered. The states and county layers are from ESRI. Environmental Systems Research Institute, Inc. The NFS layer is from GSTC (Geospatial Service and Technology Center), 2222 West 2300 South, Salt Lake City, Utah 84119 Dr. Robert Bailey's Ecoregions: <http://www.fs.fed.us/institute/ecoregions/eco_download.html> or <http://nationalatlas.gov/atlasftp.html>

horizpa.horizpar: The FVS Location Code shapefile shows discrete boundaries created by using the state, county, Bailey's Ecolines and national forests layers. Though the boundaries are discrete, the information represented is continuous. The lcoation codes may be up to 2000 meter off as that is the resolution accuracy of the underlying reference sources. The choice to use a location code for a project is not hampered since the map gives ADVICE as to which location code may be most appropriate.

overview.eaover: The boundaries of the location codes were determined using National Forest and National Forest district boundaries. In addition, Bureau of Land Management and Bureau of Indian Affairs boundaries were used where appropriate. Where location codes had to be expanded beyond the geographic range of the data used to develop them, or where location codes overlap, attempts were made to follow geographic, ecological, or political boundaries. In cases where there is no clear boundary to follow, best judgement was used.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: This GIS layer was designed to provide a default FVS variant and location code information for any location within the United States based solely on its coordinates. An example of its intended use is the automated assignment of default variants and location codes to a large number of points based on latitude and longitude alone. It is important to understand that the codes in this layer are suggested defaults only.
dataIdInfo.idAbs: The Forest Vegetation Simulator (FVS) is the USDA Forest Service's nationally supported framework for forest growth and yield modeling. A 'variant' is a model calibrated to a specific geographic area. Within each variant, location codes are used to adjust model parameters and determine volume equations. In most variants, location codes are assigned as a standardized code that identifies a national forest or a specific district, but there are a few exceptions. In this GIS layer most FVS location codes have been assigned based on the proclaimed forest boundaries (not administrative boundaries). Areas outside of national forest boundaries have been assigned location codes based on proximity and similarity to national forest lands. There has been exactly one variant and one location code assigned for every location within the United States. Each polygon represents the location code that could be used as the default based on geographic location alone. This layer is not intended to identify the only variant and location code, nor even the best for any particular location, and a user of the FVS model is free to select whatever variant and location code they feel is appropriate for their data. Please refer to the FVS documentation (Variant Overviews) for a description of the geographic extent of the data used to develop each variant.
